# The National Database of Childcare Prices (NDCP) provides detailed estimates of childcare costs across U.S. counties between 2008 and 2018. The data is broken down by state, county, care type (center-based vs. family-based), age group (infant, toddler, preschool), and percentile pricing (median and 75th percentile). Each cost variable is supplemented with a quality flag indicating the reliability of the estimate.

# Using this dataset, I explored trends in pricing growth over time, regional disparities in childcare aSordability, and the higher burden of infant care costs. Several patterns emerged that can help inform policymakers, families, and researchers.

# Key Findings: Infant care is the most expensive: Center-based infant care in high-cost regions regularly exceeds $1,500/month. Costs increase as children get younger, making care least aSordable when families have the fewest financial resources. Large geographic disparities: Cost diSerences between states can exceed $1,000/month. Urban counties such as those in California, Massachusetts, New York consistently rank highest. Costs rising faster than wages: Between 2008–2018, infant care costs increased every year nationally. Salary growth did not keep pace, especially for single-parent households. Family-based care oSers some relief: Even the “cheaper” option can consume a substantial share of household income. These patterns aligned with expectations from Milestone 2’s medium planning Milestone 2 and informed the visuals developed in Milestone 3.
